---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import GlobeHero from '../components/GlobeHero.astro';
import DelayHeatmap from '../components/DelayHeatmap.astro';
import CrossfilterDash from '../components/CrossfilterDash.astro';
import AnomalyList from '../components/AnomalyList.astro';
import ForecastChart from '../components/ForecastChart.astro';
import summary from '@data/airport_summary.json';

const airports = [
  { code: 'IAD', name: 'Dulles',  color: 'var(--iad)', ...summary.IAD },
  { code: 'DCA', name: 'Reagan',  color: 'var(--dca)', ...summary.DCA },
  { code: 'BWI', name: 'BWI',     color: 'var(--bwi)', ...summary.BWI },
] as const;

function pct(n: number) { return (n * 100).toFixed(1) + '%'; }
function fmt(n: number) { return n.toLocaleString(); }
function fmtk(n: number) { return n >= 1_000_000 ? (n / 1_000_000).toFixed(2) + 'M' : n >= 1_000 ? (n / 1_000).toFixed(0) + 'K' : String(n); }
---

<Layout>
  <GlobeHero />

  <!-- ── Section 1: Introduction ─────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section>
    <div class="prose">
      <h2>IAD, DCA, BWI — what ten years of data shows</h2>
      <p>
        Growing up in the DMV means you've always got three airports to pick from. IAD out
        in Chantilly, DCA right by the Potomac, BWI up in Baltimore. All within 40 miles of
        each other, all serving the same metro area, all somehow feeling completely different.
      </p>
      <p>
        I live closest to IAD so it's usually my default, and my flights to Taiwan go through
        there — though even IAD requires a layover for that route, so it's not like you're
        getting anything special over the other two. One summer I found Tokyo cheaper out of
        BWI than anything IAD was offering, which caught me off guard since I'd always assumed
        IAD had the best international fares. Most recently I flew out of IAD for Tampa for a
        cruise. Every time, the thing actually driving the decision was price. Pick the cheapest
        option and work backwards from there — I think that's how most people do it.
      </p>
      <p>
        So I pulled the data. <strong>3.2 million flights</strong> from January 2015 through
        January 2026 — 2,823,044 domestic and 335,719 international departures — joined with
        NOAA weather records, T-100 capacity data, and DB1B fare surveys.
        Here's what ten years actually shows.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Stat cards -->
    <div class="cards full-bleed">
      {airports.map(ap => (
        <div class="card">
          <div class="card-code" style={`color: ${ap.color}`}>{ap.code}</div>
          <div class="card-name">{ap.name}</div>
          <div class="card-stats">
            <div class="stat">
              <span class="stat-value">{fmt(ap.total_flights + (ap as any).intl_departures)}</span>
              <span class="stat-label">total flights</span>
            </div>
            <div class="stat">
              <span class="stat-value">{pct(ap.late_rate)}</span>
              <span class="stat-label">arrived late†</span>
            </div>
            <div class="stat">
              <span class="stat-value">{pct(ap.cancel_rate)}</span>
              <span class="stat-label">cancelled†</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card-intl">+{fmtk((ap as any).intl_departures)} intl departures</div>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
    <p class="cards-footnote full-bleed">† Domestic flights only — BTS on-time data covers domestic routes. "Arrived late" = 15+ min behind scheduled arrival.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Section 2: Crossfilter ───────────────────────────────── -->
  <section>
    <div class="prose">
      <h2>Explore 3.2 million flights</h2>
      <p>
        Filter by airport, then drag to select a range on hour or month, and click
        individual bars on the delay and distance charts to toggle them. Every chart
        updates based on the selections in all the others — so if you filter to
        morning flights in June, you immediately see how that changes the delay
        distribution.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="section-chart prose">
      <CrossfilterDash />
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Section 3: Delay heatmaps ──────────────────────────────── -->
  <section>
    <div class="prose">
      <h2>When delays happen</h2>
      <p>
        Morning flights are consistently the most reliable across all three airports.
        Summer (June–August) and winter (December–January) push late rates highest.
        Evening departures in July and August are the worst single combination —
        particularly at BWI, where the 6–9 pm window in summer tops 30%.
      </p>
      <p>
        Select an airport to explore its hour × month delay pattern. Each cell shows
        the fraction of flights that arrived more than 15 minutes late.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="section-chart prose">
      <DelayHeatmap />
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Section 4: Anomalous routes ───────────────────────────── -->
  <section>
    <div class="prose">
      <h2>Routes that keep misbehaving</h2>
      <p>
        Isolation Forest flagged 87 routes as persistently anomalous since 2022 —
        meaning their delay profile is a consistent outlier from the rest of the network,
        year after year. BWI dominates with 42 such routes, followed by DCA (30) and IAD (15).
        BWI→ATL has been flagged every year for five consecutive years.
      </p>
      <p>
        The bar shows how many of the post-2022 years each route was flagged.
        A route that scores 5/5 has been anomalous every year since 2022.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="section-chart prose">
      <AnomalyList />
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Section 5: Forecasts ──────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section>
    <div class="prose">
      <h2>What the models say</h2>
      <p>
        Prophet models were fitted on monthly late rates from 2015–2021 and
        projected through 2026. The dashed line is the forecast; solid lines are actuals.
        The shaded band is the 95% confidence interval.
      </p>
      <p>
        IAD and DCA are tracking close to forecast. BWI is the outlier: it spiked
        well above its expected trend starting in 2022 and has only partially recovered —
        averaging +4 percentage points above forecast through 2024.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="section-chart prose">
      <ForecastChart />
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Section 6: Limitations ────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section>
    <div class="prose">
      <h2>Limitations</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>No international delay data — BTS on-time performance covers domestic flights only. International route arcs on the globe show passenger volume, not delays.</li>
        <li>No international fare data — DB1B is domestic only by design.</li>
        <li>NOAA weather coverage ends August 2025; 4.5% of rows have no weather features.</li>
        <li>DB1B is a 10% ticket sample — fare figures are estimates.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  /* Stat cards */
  .cards {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
    gap: 1rem;
    margin-top: 2.5rem;
    padding: 0 1.5rem;
  }
  @media (max-width: 640px) {
    .cards {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      padding: 0 1.25rem;
      margin-top: 1.75rem;
    }
    .card { padding: 1.25rem; }
    .card-code { font-size: 1.5rem; }
  }
  .card {
    background: var(--surface);
    border-radius: 12px;
    padding: 1.5rem;
    border: 1px solid #2a2d3a;
  }
  .card-code {
    font-size: 2rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
    line-height: 1;
  }
  .card-name {
    color: var(--muted);
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    margin: 0.25rem 0 1.25rem;
  }
  .card-stats {
    display: flex;
    gap: 1.25rem;
  }
  .card-intl {
    margin-top: 0.65rem;
    font-size: 0.72rem;
    color: var(--muted);
    border-top: 1px solid #2a2d3a;
    padding-top: 0.5rem;
  }
  .stat {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.125rem;
  }
  .stat-value {
    font-size: 1.125rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: #fff;
  }
  .stat-label {
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    color: var(--muted);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
  }

  .section-chart {
    margin-top: 0;
  }
  .cards-footnote {
    font-size: 0.72rem;
    color: var(--muted);
    margin-top: 0.75rem;
    padding: 0 1.5rem;
  }

  ul {
    padding-left: 1.25rem;
    color: var(--text);
  }
  ul li {
    margin-bottom: 0.6rem;
  }
</style>
